Overview

This is a report looking at the differences between DESeq2 and ZINB-WaVE + DESeq2 for doing differential expression calls on inDrop data. This report grew out of a discussion with Mike Love, Koen Van den Berge and Mike Steinbaugh on the Bioconductor support site here. To summarize, we noticed that we were missing calls in ZINB-WaVE weighted data at the low end of expression where calls that looked specific to one condition appeared like they were being missed. See the link to the discussion above for some more information.

Data background

This is an inDrop dataset of cells consisting of 1864 cells after quality control and filtering. The cells are from different parts of an organ, in a wildtype and mutant mouse. For this example, we want to look at the different between the wt_anterior and the mutant_anterior cells in group 0. There are 4240 cells in group 0, 351 are wt_anterior cells and 351 are mutant_anterior cells.

Preprocessing

We pulled the raw data out of our Seurat object, created a SummarizedExperiment object from it and ran and saved the ZINB-WaVE weight calculations. We then made two DESeqDataSet objects, one with the weights called dds_weights and one without called dds_noweights. The script to do that is in make-example-objects.R and is quoted below:

library(Seurat)
library(tidyverse)
library(zinbwave)
library(DESeq2)

load("data/seurat.rda")

## Make SE object from Seurat object
metadata = seurat@meta.data
metadata$genoregion = as.factor(paste(metadata$genotype, metadata$region, sep="_"))
counts = seurat@raw.data
counts = counts[Matrix::rowSums(counts >= 5) >= 5, ]
metadata$genoregion = gsub("anerior", "anterior", metadata$genoregion)
metadata$genotype = gsub("anerior", "anterior", metadata$genotype)
se = SummarizedExperiment(assays=list(counts=as.matrix(counts)),
                          colData=metadata)


## create and save dds object with ZINB-WaVE weights
weight_fn = file.path("data", "dds-weights.rda")
design = model.matrix(~genoregion, data=colData(se))
epsilon_de = 1e12
zinb = zinbFit(se, K=0, epsilon=epsilon_de, BPPARAM=BiocParallel::SerialParam(),
                X = design)
counts_zinb = zinbwave(se, fitted_model = zinb, K = 0, epsilon=epsilon_de)
dds_weights = DESeqDataSet(counts_zinb, design=~1+genoregion)
save(dds_weights, file=weight_fn)

## create and save dds object without weights
noweight_fn = file.path("data", "dds-noweights.rda")
ddsraw = DESeqDataSet(se, design=~1+genoregion)
save(ddsraw, file=noweight_fn)

We pulled in the two DESeqDataSets and subset them to the cells in group 0. These are dds_g0_weights and dds_g0_noweights.

Comparison of DESeq2 and DESeq2 + ZINB-WaVE

The p-values arent really correlated to each other across much of the range, but the LFCs are:

results = data.frame(symbol=rownames(g0_weights_results),
                     baseMean=g0_weights_results$baseMean,
                     weights_pval=g0_weights_results$pvalue,
                     weights_padj=g0_weights_results$padj,
                     weights_lfc=g0_weights_results$log2FoldChange,
                     weights_lfcSE=g0_weights_results$lfcSE,
                     noweights_pval=g0_noweights_results$pvalue,
                     noweights_lfc=g0_noweights_results$log2FoldChange,
                     noweights_lfcSE=g0_noweights_results$lfcSE,
                     noweights_padj=g0_noweights_results$padj)
ggplot(results, aes(weights_pval, noweights_pval)) +
  geom_point() +
  xlab("weighted p-value") +
  ylab("unweighted p-value")

ggplot(results, aes(weights_lfc, noweights_lfc)) +
  geom_point() +
  xlab("weighted LFC") +
  ylab("unweighted LFC")

weighted_siggenes = subset(results, weights_padj < 0.05)$symbol
noweighted_siggenes = subset(results, noweights_padj < 0.05)$symbol
allsig = union(weighted_siggenes, noweighted_siggenes)
both = intersect(weighted_siggenes, noweighted_siggenes)
weighted_specific = weighted_siggenes[!weighted_siggenes %in% noweighted_siggenes]
noweighted_specific = noweighted_siggenes[!noweighted_siggenes %in% weighted_siggenes]

The unweighted results are a superset of the weighted results.

setinfo = list(weighted=weighted_siggenes, unweighted=noweighted_siggenes)
UpSetR::upset(fromList(setinfo))

results$present = ifelse(results$symbol %in% both, "both",
                         ifelse(results$symbol %in% noweighted_specific,
                                "noweighted_specific", "notsig"))

The unweighted-specific genes are distributed across the baseMean spectrum, so it isnt specifically low or high genes we are missing.

ggplot(results, aes(baseMean)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_wrap(~present) +
  scale_x_log10()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

We are missing calls for large LFC genes with the ZINB-WaVE weighted calls, but there are differences across the spectrum.

ggplot(results, aes(weights_lfc, noweights_lfc)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  facet_wrap(~present) +
  xlab("weighted LFC") +
  ylab("unweighted LFC")

Its possible that DESeq2 is calling too liberally with no weights and too strict with ZINB-WaVE weights though.

low baseMean, high LFC genes

I selected genes with a LFC > 10 and a baseMean > 0.3. If we include all of the facets, these dont look super impressive:

low = as.character(subset(results, abs(noweights_lfc) > 10 & baseMean > 0.3)$symbol)
lowdat = counts(dds_g0_noweights)[low,] %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  tibble::rownames_to_column("symbol") %>%

  left_join(colData(dds_noweights) %>%
            as.data.frame() %>%
            tibble::rownames_to_column("cell")) %>%
  left_join(results)
## Joining, by = "cell"
## Joining, by = "symbol"
ggplot(lowdat, aes(symbol, UMI, color=genoregion)) +

But if we subset down to just the contrasts we are interested in, they do look like they should be called DE, and DESeq2 alone calls most of these.

Summary

ZINB-WaVE weights are causing a lot of what appear to be false negatives to me in this inDrop dataset. Theres been some talk that there may not be a need to add a zero inflated component to experiments that use UMIs (see this paper) for example.
